            <div class = "hero">
                <h1>Eliminating Systematic Bias in Medical Research and Practice</h1>
                <h4 style = "color: #6935B3">Why our mission matters for healthcare equality </h4>
            </div>
            
            <p>
                For decades, medical research has operated on a "male-as-default" model. This systematic bias in research and practice has long been a barrier to equitable healthcare. Because women are frequently underrepresented in clinical trials, researchers often fail to consider sex-specific biological variablesâ€”such as hormonal cycles or different body structuresâ€”that drastically change how a body reacts to treatment.
            </p>
            <p>
                The Consequences of Exclusion When a drug's dosage or a medical device's safety is tested primarily on men, the results are fundamentally biased. This leads to dangerous situations where women are prescribed medications that may be ineffective or even gravely dangerous due to higher toxicity levels or adverse reactions. A prime example is The Ambien Scale: women were prescribed the same dose as men for decades before it was discovered they metabolize the drug much slower, leading to a significantly higher rate of accidents.
            </p>
            <p>
                Our Solution At MediBias, we are dedicated to identifying these biases and promoting inclusivity in medical research and practice. Our platform provides:
            </p>
            <div class = "grid">
                <a href="#stats" onclick="showSection('stats')" style="text-decoration: none; color: inherit;">
                    <article style = "background-color: #DECFED;">
                        <header style = "background-color: #D3BFE8;"><strong>Past - Research Statistics </strong></header>
                        <p style = "color: #6935B3">A searchable database showing the current representation levels in medical research.</p> 
                    </article>
                </a>
                <a href="#tracker" onclick="showSection('tracker')" style="text-decoration: none; color: inherit;">
                    <article style = "background-color: #DECFED;">
