        <section id="silence">
            <div class = "hero">
                <h2>The Silence Gallery</h2>
            </div>
            <p>A collection of stories and case studies highlighting overlooked groups in medical research. Evidence of life-threatning neglect in women's healthcare research.</p>
            <div class = "grid">
                <article>
                    <header><strong> Harvard Medical School Study </strong></header>
                    <p style = "color: #6935B3">In 2022, a Harvard Medical School study finds that women, as of 2019, were still substantially underrepresented in clinical trials for leading diseases.</p> 
                </article>
                <article>
                    <header><strong> Thalidomide Case </strong></header>
                    <p style = "color: #6935B3">In the late 1950s, in Europe and Australia thalidomide was marketed as a safe sedative for morning sickness, yet it caused a catastrophic medical tragedy. Over 10,000 babies were born with severe limb deformities, and thousands died, highlighting the devastating cost of excluding pregnant women from rigorous safety testing.</p> 
                </article>
            </div>
            <div class = "grid">
                <article>
                    <header><strong> The Ambien Scale</strong></header>
                    <p style = "color: #6935B3">Women were prescribed the same dose as men for decades before the FDA realized women metabolize it much slower, leading to high accident rates.</p> 
                </article>
                <article>
                    <header><strong> Misdiagnosis of Pain and Autoimmune Diseases </strong></header>
                    <p style = "color: #6935B3">Chronic pain is more prevalent in women, yet studies suggest it is sometimes undertreated compared to men, with women potentially receiving less pain medication after identical surgeries. This research neglect delays autoimmune and endometriosis diagnoses by years, forcing many into prolonged suffering or costly private care due to historically biased funding priorities.</p> 
                </article>
            </div>
            <article>
                <header><strong> Refrences </strong></header>
                <ul>
                    <li> "Pharma Almanac. (2024, April 1)." <i>Pain, misdiagnosis, and sutoimmune disease: Untangling Complexity and bias.</i> <a href="https://www.pharmasalmanac.com/articles/pain-misdiagnosis-and-autoimmune-disease-untangling-complexity-and-bias"></a></li>
                    <li> "Balch, B. (2024, March 26)." <i>Why we know so little about women's health.</i> "AAMC" <a href="https://www.aamc.org/news/why-we-know-so-little-about-women-s-health"></a></li>
                    <li> "Westergaard, D., Moseley, P., Sorup, F. K. H., Baldi, P., & Brunak, S. (2019)." <i>Population-wide analysis of differences in disease progression patterns in men and women. Nature Communications, 10(1), 1-14.</i><a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4800017/#_ci93_"></a></li>
                </ul>
            </article>        
